author: Pavel Zykin
text: Got one in April 2018. This instrument is unbelievably cheap so at the time of buying I have not had hight expectation for it. I was wrong! This instrument is really good seems like a copy of JINBAO JBEP - 1150 but in different finish. The intonation and tuneability is pretty good I have not been able to found any major drawbacks. There are, however, some points of concern. Firstly, the valves have to be actively used for a week or more to become responsive enough, so buy a bottle of valve oil along with the instrument and re-oil the valves daily for the first week.  Secondly the main turning slider is a little bit stiff: nothing to worry about unless you plan to install a DIY trigger on the instrument. The mouthpiece it a bit rough I've polished it's rim and now it is perfect. All in all - a really good compensating instrument for the money: free blowing, tunable, with good intonation and a hard case for long distance travelling.

author: Gerardo
text: A couple of months ago I got a Monzani Soprano Sax, and I was simply surprised about the quality and sound but this time my experience with the Monzani Tenor Sax was not as good.The Monzani Tenor Sax came with some sound problems, I realised that he mechanism of the octave key wasn't accurate enough, some air was leaking, the little cushion on the sax neck wasn't covering the hole accurate enough, I had to decide between calling for a replacement or try to fix it myself (I live in Russia so it would be a long process for devolution).Practically the problem was in the "neck" it was so cheap and not accurate, twisted, wrenched, the little arm that forces the pad to close the octave hole was going to the side and not strong enough. I fixed it by myself but I think it will survive not for long, I will have to order another neck.Looks like the manufacture of the neck is really poor and amateur, it even shows some traces of scratches and not an accurate job. Any other than that, all the rest of the Sax works perfectly and the price is simply unbeatable. I want to mention that in the sax case, there are a couple of spots that are fitting too tight on some of the sax keys, on the higher part, an inside adjustment on that would do great. Anyway, it is great that for such price they include this case which after all is good enough, good looking and Im thankful to Musicstore for this affordable opportunity.Tracking number provided, safely packed, affordable shipment price, it took around 10 working days to reach Kazan, Russia.

author: Igor Lapshin
text: At first there were ambiguities with the correct installation on the seven-string tremolo system. Tighten the bolts to the maximum in the deck. Removed 2 springs from 4 and Temmori put the third in the center. In my opinion, after that, the sustain was weakened, and the work with the tremolo lever became too soft. I have increased the tension by adding another spring putting it in the center and tremmori to the second position from 1 st string. In the result I have the following arrangement of springs in holes in the next sequence from the bottom (1st string) to the top (6st string): 1-spring, 2 - tremmori, 3- spring, 4 - empty, 5, - empty, 6 - spring. I satisfied with the stability of the tuning of the guitar now.

author: Eugene Dovganich
text: Neutron is versatile machine for sound design, that gives a lot for little investments.Sound and build quality are the strong points of this instrument. Complex enough to investigate its limits for months!There is a con, that make workflow a bit annoying. Neutron's default routing: signal path automatically goes thru overdrive and you must spend some amount of patch points to disable overdrive, instead of being able to patch it manually when it's needed. The same is for delay,But after all, I think, this synth is awesome piece of gear, that I would recommend to try to everyone!
topic: Good starting point in modular synths

author: Evgeny
text: It is very original synth and you definitely will like it if your goal is experimenting with modulations and not getting classic lush analog sounds. The filter got some clipping, Distortion circuit slightly limits frequency range, but it's totally fine, just an unusual character. Patchbay is not perfectly normalized, but it gets the job done.The main drawback is digital LFO that starts to generate all sorts of digital noise as you increase frequency past 1kHz. However, alternate open firmware can easily fix that issue and even add third oscillator mode to LFO and few other cool features.

author: Gerardo
text: I really like Legere plastic reeds, this is my second one, I have got one for my Soprano Sax and one for my Tenor Sax. One of these plastic reeds would cost you the same as a full box of wooden reeds, but this Legere reed will last virtually forever. I like the warm tone it projects, there is no need to damp it, lick it, you engage action instantly, but consider that it doesn't absorb saliva, saliva would collect beneath, so every 10-15 minutes playing you have to take the reed out of the ligature to clean it. One more great thing, if you are fan of hygiene, you can use mouth wash to clean this reed after each performance or practice.A technical point I want to mention, seems to me these reeds are a little bit harder than the indicated number so I would advice order half a number lower, or one number lower than what you usually use. Ex. If I like 2.5 wooden reeds, then on Legere I would get a 2.0

author: Gerardo
text: A couple of months ago I got a Monzani Soprano Sax, and I was simply surprised about the quality and sound but this time my experience with the Monzani Tenor Sax was not as good.The Monzani Tenor Sax came with some sound problems, I realised that he mechanism of the octave key wasn't accurate enough, some air was leaking, the little cushion on the sax neck wasn't covering the hole accurate enough, I had to decide between calling for a replacement or try to fix it myself (I live in Russia so it would be a long process for devolution).Practically the problem was in the "neck" it was so cheap and not accurate, twisted, wrenched, the little arm that forces the pad to close the octave hole was going to the side and not strong enough. I fixed it by myself but I think it will survive not for long, I will have to order another neck.Looks like the manufacture of the neck is really poor and amateur, it even shows some traces of scratches and not an accurate job. Any other than that, all the rest of the Sax works perfectly and the price is simply unbeatable. I want to mention that in the sax case, there are a couple of spots that are fitting too tight on some of the sax keys, on the higher part, an inside adjustment on that would do great. Anyway, it is great that for such price they include this case which after all is good enough, good looking and Im thankful to Musicstore for this affordable opportunity.Tracking number provided, safely packed, affordable shipment price, it took around 10 working days to reach Kazan, Russia.

author: –ú–∏—Ö–∞–∏–ª
text: I was looking for a precision chorus in a Pedalboard. There Was An Agular Chorusaurus. But he upset me with the fact that when you turn on the effect, the volume changed and a little timbre.. and constantly "chewed" the bottom. I couldn't find a working mode that would play both natural bass and light chorus. I reviewed a lot of choruses, stopped at MXR and do not regret it. When you turn on the pedal, it accurately transmits the timbre of the instrument and adding effect, the sound is not washed, but remains familiar only with the chorus!) That's what I was looking for. I expected a little different from the X-OVER button. I thought that it just releases the signal below 100Hz from the chorus and the bottom remains intact. It turned out that this is so, but then there is a compensation of the bottom and this gives the effect of EQ. That is, pressing the button adds a bottom of about 40-60 Hz and it is heard very much and it is not regulated..!. I didn't like it at all.. EQ work smoothly and do not strain.. The main thing is that I got what I wanted!) Not cheap, but when you're looking for sound, money doesn't really count)).. Recommend. Good luck to all!! Michael. Moscow.

author: Aleksei
text: First of all I should to say that I have had play experience only with amp sims before so that this review is written impressed by difference between digital and analogue worlds.Build quality and appearance are certainly on high level. Knobs turns smoothly bright switcher has no excessive play and that also applies to other components. The Kraken has great weight (comparing with usual pedals) and looks solid. As Boris The Blade used to say Heavy is good, Heavy is reliable. If it doesn't work you can always hit them with it.Now I'll tell about minor negative thing. I was having high-pitched continuous beep after some time of work when I plugged it to multi-power supply (12V 1000mA and with isolated outputs claimed by the manufacturer). I had to switch to kraken's power supply so now it's ok. I think it's probably more problem with multi-power supply.Ok let's talk about the most important thing it is SOUND. My rig includes Clean Booster -> Overdrive pedal -> The Kraken -> Audio Interface -> Wall of Sound. In general it allows me to reach my purpose to get high gain sound for metal tones on red chanel. Maybe with 4 cable method connection with real amp it works better but in standalone mode it still needs some boosted impulse from pre-overdrive if you want to get tight punchy rithm to play with palm mute. So I wouldnt consider it as extremely high gain sound. But it doesn't diminish the greate tone of the Kraken at all it still does most of work of creating tone. I used it togheter with Kraken 412 speaker simulation and it works very well. Regarding sound itself comparing with amp simulators it is on couple levels above. I don't know how to explain, it feels more musical, touch sensetive, clear without mud and some noisy unmusical high frequensies that I get on sims. I can play for hours and I don't get earn fatigue. My ass and left leg get tired faster. And litteraly yesterday before I started write this review I discovered how amazing sounds natural harmonics. You can produce it on the several strings simulteniously e.g. and I don't know how to properly explain this feeling but at this moment you clearly understand that it works just as nature intended. By the way string difinition is also fantastic. Speaking of how it works with extended range guitars. I use 8 string guitar in standart tuning and it still sounds very well. Maybe it looses a bit to big brother but with proper cab you can get tight tone. After digital amps I'm a bit shocked and surprised. And I think that proper IR makes about 30% percent of work if not more.All in all I would strongly recommend it for those who are tired of amp sims and looking for better sound for playing in bedroom.
topic: Good first step towards to world of analog sound

author: Dmitriy
text: High-quality built-in sounds. However, it should be noted that this pedal is very specific and requires the preparation of the instrumental signal. Therefore, in order to make it authentic to imitate the built-in sounds, you will have to work hard in preparing the signal: in terms of level, in frequency response and especially in attack and in attenuation. For some musical instruments in general, it will be difficult to achieve adequate and predictable MEL9 performance. Particularly noteworthy is the very incorrect work of the pedal directly with the instrumental piezoelectric transducers. Actually it can also be attributed to the entire line of Machine Electro Harmonix (KEY9, C9, B9). In any case, if you really need authentic sounds embedded in these pedals, then you can achieve their imitation, but not out of the box ... or you will be forced to put up with artifacts arising from the unbalanced instrumentality.

author: Tim
text: In general, I am satisfied.There is a very good middle, pleasantly cut off the top.Wonderful neck - "fast", in my opinion. Strings are not planted high - very comfortable!With capo you can safely use up to the 5th fret. If you need higher, then you have to twist the tool for yourself - change the threshold for a little more. As I was told in the Ortega support service, the bone threshold, keep in mind.I immediately replaced the strings on La Bella  extra hard tension and the sound improved.In my opinion, the only drawback is that the guitar does not have such low frequencies, which I expected from mahogany and therefore somewhat distressed. The body on bottoms does not resonate enough, perhaps this is only in my specimen, and perhaps this is due to the painting of the tool, which is unnecessary, though beautiful.In general, the sound is very smooth, soft and nothing sticks out.The built-in tuner is beyond praise! I no longer use the Polytune tuner, although both are great.Did not connect through the wire. So with this I can not describe anything.

author: Dmitriy
text: I'm not a professional nor a keyboard player but still I am fully satisfied with this keyboard. It doesn't have weighted keys but I never intended to be a professional piano player. The keybed just feels good, velocity sensitivity is on point. I don't know how it is with other keyboards, but black keys are a bit harder to push than white. Nonetheless, it's just the matter of time for you to get used to it. I am yet to explore all the possibilities of this keyboard (used it actively for 2 weeks) and I cannot rate it's software, but just as a midi-controller - I'd dare to say it is among the best. It just screams quallity. I use it with FL Studio and it connects perfectly fine! This keyboard doesn't need power supply, it just works via USB.I composed several keyboard compositions inside my DAW in piano roll and it is such a pleasure to be able to play them and learn them, as funny as it may sound. Gee, I didn't even mentioned the screens because I didn't use them yet! Also, it was delivered to Russia safe and sound (pun unintended) with a lot of padding inside the box. I chose 61-key version just because of where I live. I just can't afford a keyboard to take a lot of space and be super heavy live ones with weighted keys and I still want to be able to learn and compose piano pieces. And yes, the smaller range limits me a bit, but in rare occasions. It is just the compromise I had to make unfortunately.In general, It is a pricey piece of gear, but in my point it's worth its money. Thank you Music Store!

author: Igor Lapshin
product_name: Fireball 100 E 635 Guitar Ampl ifier Head
text: The clean channel of Fireball is very beautiful, voluminous, sparkling, truly three-dimensional. This sound fills the entire room and as if envelops your notes. A sharp punchy clear sound is really good, but by adding a little overdrive with the Clean Gain knob, we get an unreal sound. Most guitarists will be able to play an entire concert on this channel with the handle of the gain twisted to the right. On a clear channel there is a Bright switch, it is optimally tuned and makes your sound more vivid, without busting. That is necessary. With this switch, you can revive the sound of your humbuckers and make the sound of your Stratocaster singles even more resonant.Even at high volumes, this sound does not become coarser, but, on the contrary, even more saturated and surround. Even super clear sound sounds very long and the feedback is really musical. Fine!Turning on the Lead channel, we instantly got resilient, aggressive distortion, which is what ENGL amplifiers are known for. Take the full range of the Lead Gain control you can use. With minimal settings, you get a cool rocky bite sound, at higher overload values, it just washes you away with a stream of metal. There is everything you need: overload, sustain and excellent flageolets. No matter how much overload we tuned on this amplifier, we could still play minor and major chords with extra steps, and these chords sounded! Usually with this level of overload chords are blurred. Surprisingly, all the notes sounded clean and expressive. Although, most likely, guitarists playing on this amplifier channel will not use such steps in chords.Changing to dropped-D, we began to play riffs with palm-muting. Turning on the additional Bottom mode (it affects both channels at once), we received a very large, powerful sound, while maintaining extraordinary clarity. No matter how many bottoms we wore, the top still sparkled. Awesome At the same time ENGL Fireball is very quiet, partly due to the built-in noise gate, the threshold of which is regulated on the rear panel of the amplifier. Depending on which footswitch you connect to your Fireball, you can switch channels, Mid Boost, Master A / B, and turn on / off FX loop. As a result, you have very flexible settings, many options, it is very convenient to work on stage. That is why so many modern guitarists use Engl. These are great sounding amplifiers with a more than reasonable price.

Actually it can also be attributed to the entire line of Machine Electro Harmonix (MEL9, C9, B9). text: This is a ‚ÄúGhost‚Äù signature model made by Swedish company Hagstrom. I decided to buy this guitar after watching the band live . I was impressed by the way their guitars sounded and looked. First of all - the look, it is pretty big and not light , but you just feel the power when it is in your hands. Next , the sound , no ...THE SOUND. Classical Alnico pickups were elevated by Johan Lundgren. I really have never heard of him before , but it is magic. This guitar doesn‚Äôt forgive any mistakes while playing due to its absolutely crazy legibility. It pronounces every touch and it gives you an incredible control. Another thing about pickups is an ability to play them as singles. It really can deliver you that very Fender-like glass sound. And it makes the guitar really versatile. The tuning machines and other accessories are specially designed and look really nice and organic with the instrument. This is the guitar that can be everything you want it to be. An elegant jazzy tone or a metal axe. As for its price - it is really fare. But the pleasure is just priceless.

author: Igor
text: I have Zoom G1Xon, MS50G  and lately decided to buy new G3Xn (before that I owned G3X but sold it after 2 days). What is good:1. Great sounding amps models - I'm not a fan of amp modelling and will never buy a Kemper but sometimes when you play direct to PA you have to use amp modelling of some kind. Zoom G3Xn have much better algorithms than my previous models.2. Built quality - solid metal, much better than my plastic G1Xon.3. Compact, quick editing of any of 3 effects parameters.What is bad:1. Sucks tone a little2. Expression pedal can operate only with certain effects - WAH, Pedal Delay, Pedal Reverb and some more. So you cannot assign pedal to operate any parameter of any effect - that's ridiculous. Even my cheap G1Xon can do so,3. No MAX and MIN setting for pedal operations - it always goes from 0 to 100. 4. No effects spillover when changing patch - if you play patch #1 with Delay with long feedback and then switch to patch#2 - your Delay tails will go off instantly. Thats very sad.5. Stupid idea to make looper and drummachine as separate effects - so you have to put them into the certain patch if you want to jam along. But if you change patch - your loop is gone.6. No patch editing capability in Zoom Sound Librarian softrawe for G3Xn - you can just rename patches and reorganize them.  But if you want to buid patch from scratch or edit effects parameters - no way. Just from G3Xn internal menu.

author: Anton
text: First of all, this a beautiful-looking guitar. I've always wanted a Guild, but even the 90's Fender-made reissues cost a lot nowadays. This is a cult piece of gear nevertheless and is rightfully revered among grunge and stoner rock guitarists for it's unique look and tone. This is a Korean-made reissue which is at least truthful to original looks. It's stunning and feels really well-made. The finish is nice and glossy, the knobs and tuners feel sturdy, no loose frets, and the original bridge piece is made of solid metal. It was alright to play right outside of the box, and all electronics worked, but of course it needs to be taken to the luthier to improve the action and feel. Also, it would be cool to have a roller bridge and coil split option as on the originals, but it always can be done later as an upgrade. It also comes in a nice gig-bag which is always a plus.As a player, this guitar is really light! Of course it comes at a cost of little neck dive - not that crucial as on the SG but it certainly is here.  The neck itself is a little too wide for my taste but pretty comfortable. The sound is somewhere between the SG and Les Paul - meaty and a little nasal (in a good way) but surprisingly bright, which, I suppose, is a matter of Guild's original pickups. They sound (and look) great, and I don't see the need to change them anytime soon.All in all, the only drawback would be the price. Of course, this item costs less than a half of vintage american-made Guild Polara, and it's really well made, but the purists could consider buying a used Gibson for the money. author: Aleksei
text: I really liked this guitar, but not right away. I don't know why, maybe there was something wrong with my hearing, or maybe because before that I played the Yamaha with scalloped bracing (but not completely made of solid wood), but at first it sounded like a tin can. But after a few days I completely fell in love with her, finally I started hearing what I heard on numerous YouTube videos.As for the workmanship, everything is fine, but there is one negative point: the guy who installed the strings on this guitar must really dislike his job, because otherwise I don't understand how it can be done so badly. Bridge pins were inserted into the holes so that their grooves were not directed in the direction of the strings. One of them was directed almost perpendicular to the strings. Because of this, even the distance between the strings was not as it should be and not symmetrical. And also now there are unnecessary dents from the strings on the bridge, where they should not be, which I tried to capture on video.

author: Pavel
text: First I tried it stock, between my Marshall origin 20 and the speaker with the amp on my normal settings, but the sound instantly became mushy, no definition whatsoever.Bugera reduced the volume really well but soaked up all the highs and presence, so the sound was extremely uninspiring. I was thinking about selling the unit, but then I decided to try putting an eq pedal in the fx loop of my amp. I dialled down the mids on the eq and bumped up the highs. The results were amazing! Clear and defined sound at bedroom/night playing levels with the amps master volume almost cranked. I can recommend this unit paired with an eq pedal for all hobby players who don't have enough $$ for a high-end reactive load.Please note that even at 100% level bugera soaks up a lot of power, so your amp won't sound the same as without it and there's no way to easily bypass the box. For the price it's good, but if you can spend more look at the ox box or some higher end options.
topic: Very mushy stock, but pretty awesome with an eq pedal

author: Anton Tsvid
text: Dynaudio bm6 mkIII is really worthy nearfield! These studio monitors are very impressive that I have ever heard before they have its own character continue the legecy of company. To begin with materials that are carefully chosen that well made. If someone looking at them seemed really expensive high end product. As for features, there are all need adjustments for untutored user that are high pass filter, level settings, classic tilt filter of LF, MF, & HF. The ISOacoustic stands are included in the box that help us to find an optimal listener position. There is only one XLR input that would be enough. As for the sound, it has hi-fi influence, but quite precise natural sound so you can hear all kind of nuances by listening high quality music. These monitors have good frequency response for all spectrum: crispy highs not so ringing as metal tweeters for example that likes me very, well enough mids and low mids showing us a cool riffs & the lows have natural nice sounded bass for its size. In addition, it needs break in time hours using to achieve the best sounding. Dynaudio bm6 mkIII is really worth your attention to choose one, it can apply as control monitors and as for second pair it's up to you. The Alternatives for its price are Genelec 8040b; Focal cms65; Neuman kh120a; Dynaudio lyd7; APS Klasik; Audio a7x.... Thank's much to MusicStore! It's value for money!

author: Dmitriy
text: High-quality built-in sounds. However, it should be noted that this pedal is very specific and requires the preparation of the instrumental signal. Therefore, in order to make it authentic to imitate the built-in sounds, you will have to work hard in preparing the signal: in terms of level, in frequency response and especially in attack and in attenuation. For some musical instruments in general, it will be difficult to achieve adequate and predictable C9 performance. Particularly noteworthy is the very incorrect work of the pedal directly with the instrumental piezoelectric transducers. Actually it can also be attributed to the entire line of Machine Electro Harmonix (MEL9, KEY9, B9). In any case, if you really need authentic sounds embedded in these pedals, then you can achieve their imitation, but not out of the box ... or you will be forced to put up with artifacts arising from the unbalanced instrumentality.

(sad sad thing, but you can mod your one if you lurk on internet for guide, I guess)- Those small pins... They are not always fit well.- Built factor. author: Dmitry
text: This is my first and I dare say the last LP guitar because I've always worshipped ST curves. I was in two minds about buying EC-1000 or Kramer Baretta Vintage and,eventually, I  decided to give EMG a try.                                                          The guitar came almost in perfect conditions (the strings were bit higher that I'm used to) but it was only one tiny flaw to complain about. The matt color is bitching sexy but it prone to loose its initial appearance compared to varnished bodies in the long run. The sound is very metal and note separation is  very good too. As to neck  EMG60 clean tone, it's not so bright and clean as my Jackson with S-S-H SD  but  it's a matter of adjustments. The sound of bridge pickup provided a huge meaty metal roar and it make me put up with the LP shape). And the last but not least, the sustain is almost endless. If you still do not have LP guitar and are thinking of getting one, grab this one and  you won't regret!

author: Igor
text: An excellent series of mixer-recorders! based on such a mixer, you can easily combine the entire external setup. When improvising, using FX sends is awesome! the presence of the SUB button makes it possible to send individual channels for recording to an external looper and it is incredibly convenient. Equalizers are very organic, they are pleasant to use, although they lack "class" due to their cheapness. The built-in multi-channel recorder allows you to record all this, which allows you to completely get rid of the computer) However, I was upset by the lack of the ability to record individual channels after the equalizer and fader. With this feature, the device would make me completely satisfied.Summing up, I will say that Tascam has turned out to be an excellent tool for musicians who want to work in the style of the old school while using modern technologies. The device deserves a solid four with a bias towards five.

author: netratmail@gmail.com
text: This is my first bass, I'm just learning and have nothing to compare it to, but I could not be happier with it. I wanted to learn bass for some time and initially considered Yamaha TRBX174 and Ibanez GSR200. Then I found out that full scale basses can be hard to fret since with 34" scale length fret spacing is quite long, and there are short scale basses that don't have this problem, making them easier to learn. Ibanez GSRM29 was my first choice. I also considered Fender Squier Mini Precision (but it only has one pickup while Ibanez has two) and Cort Action Junior (also just one pickup and scale is 30" instead of 28.6" on Ibanez and Squier), but ultimately settled for Ibanez.

author: Dmitry
text: this is the best guitar I've ever had. I thought my best guitar had been Japanise Jackson with two hot rails and a humbucker in the bridge. The second one was LTD EC-1000 I bought in Music Store as well. But I must admit that my new ESP LTD Black Metal Satin is far better in my opinion than both my guitars with SD and EMG pickups. I think the name of the guitar "Black metal" is just a kind of a stereotype and may put someone off buying it if you are not a Black metal head. I do like various metal genres , however, I'm not a fan of death and black metal, but I had been 100 per cent sure that this guitar would satisfy my metal taste anyway.  I It looks agressive and it is definitely prone to metal but not only for "Black" or "Death". If you like Steel Panther or Gus G, you would be pleased with this monstrous axe! The sound provided by SD Blackened winter pickup is just what you really need to get the best metal sound ever. String separation in every chord you play is both clean and powerful simultaneously. If you want to shred, you won't regret it as well. This metal masterpice will be my favourite guitar for years!  And yes, I 've immediately taken to one H pickup and a Floyd rose-no more you need for creating a great sound. Thank you Music Store and ESP for letting me have such a great instrument!

author: Pavel Zykin
text: Got one in April 2018. This instrument is unbelievably cheap so at the time of buying I have not had hight expectation for it. I was wrong! This instrument is really good seems like a copy of JINBAO JBEP - 1150 but in different finish. The intonation and tuneability is pretty good I have not been able to found any major drawbacks. There are, however, some points of concern. Firstly, the valves have to be actively used for a week or more to become responsive enough, so buy a bottle of valve oil along with the instrument and re-oil the valves daily for the first week.  Secondly the main turning slider is a little bit stiff: nothing to worry about unless you plan to install a DIY trigger on the instrument. The mouthpiece it a bit rough I've polished it's rim and now it is perfect. All in all - a really good compensating instrument for the money: free blowing, tunable, with good intonation and a hard case for long distance travelling.

author: Dmitriy
text: High-quality built-in sounds. However, it should be noted that this pedal is very specific and requires the preparation of the instrumental signal. Therefore, in order to make it authentic to imitate the built-in sounds, you will have to work hard in preparing the signal: in terms of level, in frequency response and especially in attack and in attenuation. For some musical instruments in general, it will be difficult to achieve adequate and predictable B9 performance. Particularly noteworthy is the very incorrect work of the pedal directly with the instrumental piezoelectric transducers. Actually it can also be attributed to the entire line of Machine Electro Harmonix (MEL9, C9, KEY9). In any case, if you really need authentic sounds embedded in these pedals, then you can achieve their imitation, but not out of the box ... or you will be forced to put up with artifacts arising from the unbalanced instrumentality.

It was KORG that opened the fashion for the reincarnation of cult synthesizers in a new miniature version, while retaining the authentic sound and consistently excellent quality from KORG. In 2016, Korg Volca FM was no exception. Amazing authenticity of the sound of the Yamaha DX7 for absolutely ridiculous money and miniature sizes, what could be better ??? It should be noted that the CORG engineers made considerable efforts to make control and editing of the sound in a not so predictable FM synthesis very convenient and simple. For that money? Awesome synth.- 2 Midi-to-3.5 pin converters in box.Something about cons and in between:- Keys. Not standart, okay?- Made of plastic. Good one, but still need to be not to hard with, while travel I guess.- Monophonic. Yeah, have cool Paraphonic mode (really cool), but without fx you can hear drop in overall sound quality.This cons no too much of a headache, but I need to write some to be more objective! Overall, I can recommend this synth to anyone, exept for one who want to learn proper keys playing - get a midi or piano instead.

author: Dmitriy
text: Six years ago, KORG made a breakthrough of its kind by releasing the Volka series. I don‚Äôt think it makes sense to talk about the merits and relevance of this series among all groups of musicians. It was KORG that opened the fashion for the reincarnation of cult synthesizers in a new miniature version, while retaining the authentic sound and consistently excellent quality from KORG. In 2016, Korg Volca FM was no exception. Amazing authenticity of the sound of the Yamaha DX7 for absolutely ridiculous money and miniature sizes, what could be better ??? It should be noted that the CORG engineers made considerable efforts to make control and editing of the sound in a not so predictable FM synthesis very convenient and simple. And even took care to attach a cardboard plate with modulation algorithms included. But the most important thing is the sound, it is amazing !!!
topic: "Music Box" for the experienced and beginners ...

author: Dimix
text: This thing will help you really much if:‚Ä¢ You don‚Äôt have an access or an opportunity to control your low frequencies in the studio! These headphones are the 2 subwoofers for your ears! Fast respons allows to control the attacks and releases of your dynamic plugins or hardware immediately! That‚Äôs really important when you work on the mixing, because you spend lees time for controlling and therefore you have much time to work with any other parts of the mix before your ears get tired!‚Ä¢ Mono mode is the super feature that helps you instantly hear where you have frequency conflicts. ‚Ä¢ Cube mode is also great, because now together with mono mode you can easily control your mix the way it is going to be heard on the radio and consumer sound devices.These headphones is a must have for home studios, mobile production and etc. Having them for couple years, I really enjoy the increased speed of mixing and mastering, that gives more confident feeling while working on the music. Took that one as a present for my friend, who is also the producer. He enjoyed its modes some time ago! And now he is happy to have them in his arsenal.Special thanks to Avantone, because they create affordable professional gears that help to create exact the same sound as it is in your mind!

author: Dmitrii
text: The quality of the product is sufficient for home use: good plastic, tight buttons and a backlight that is activated when the controller is connected to electricity. The print quality is not at the highest level, perhaps after a year or two of active use it will be erased. Jogs are sufficient in size. It is inconvenient to connect cables. author: Konstantin
text: It's always been a trouble for me to bring the full-size tube head to rehearsals and gigs. I needed a small tube preamp with option to be paired with MIDI and option to use external cabsim to plug directly into a mixer without a significant tone loss. So I made a decision to buy this device.       Straight to sound - it's very decent for such a small thing. Convenient tone controls allow to shape the tone from roaring dark fuzz-like sound to somewhat british crunch. Clean channel varies from pure transistor-like clean to tubey slightly driven very light crunch (at least on active pickups). Crunch channel has a huge palette of vintage rock tones. But for something more modern it's better to use Hot Fusion mode (here's the fun, he-he-he) that boosts 2nd channel with 1st one or to use external boosters. By the way, Clean channel by itself takes well  distortions and even fuzz pedals (Big Muff clones in my case), and Crunch channel easily can be boosted to some serious level modern rock tones. I recommend to use only boosters with Crunch channel. Distortion stompboxes will turn crunch tones into a mess. I haven't found a good use to Cold fusion mode, but my fellow bassist did :) So I suppose it's more bass than guitar option. Maybe it'll be good for heavy downtuned guitars too. And yes - Le Crunch does the bass tones as easily as the guitar. Tubey tasty crunchy bass lines that's how I like it! :) Well, all in all, variety and quality of tones is the thing that made me fell in love with this pedal. Forgot to mention that tube in this preamp is not dummy, it really works as stated by the manufacturer. It glows and heats up, thus device gets warm in couple of minutes - it's normal.      Built-in cabsim is usable but not as good as decent impulse of course. I prefer to plug Le Crunch into my Torpedo C.A.B. with poweramp simulating turned on. But it sounds even better plugged into real tube poweramp (Marshall JVM210C's in my case). Don't forget - it's only a PREAMP, so it needs to be plugged into good poweramp and cabinet (or simulator) to get the tones you may like. But for home use, you can play this preamp completely standalone, just plug it into soundcard (Le Crunch has line out ant instrumental out - pay your attention), turn on some poweramp sim, cabsim and voil√†!   Also I like a tank-like metal case. I can't imagine how someone can break it without a hammer. All inputs and outputs are intuitive and carefully marked. Nothing somebody can't figure out within 5 minutes. Knobs are solid and turn precisely. Only one minus - channel switches are too far from each other, it's not always comfortable to click them on simultaneously to get into Fusion modes.    Great and very convenient preamp for the money. Use it every day (finally my rig has 20kg less weight, he-he). Tones palette, interaction with external equipment, tube coloring - all top notch in its price range. Le Crunch is not a replacement for Marshall heads, cause it has it's own tone (maybe similar to british, but slightly different, more modern), but I definitely recommend this pedal for vigorous rock rhythm and even for gorgeous solo parts. Enjoy!

product_name: FAST FRET String Cleaner and Lubricant
text: This is the best string cleaner/lubrication product I have ever used. It includes the applicator and a cloth to wipe off the excess oil which both fit in a convienient small plastic tube that can easily fit in a guitar case. It makes your strings last longer by keeping them clean, and also helps to make your strings feel more smooth/slick which makes it easier for me to play. Not only does this product do everything that it claims, but it also lasts a LONG time. I have had the same one that I use 2-4 times a week for over 3 years now! I have to admit it is now finally sort of running out of oil, but holy crap 3 years worth of quality string cleaning/lubrication for six bucks? If that's not a deal then I don't know what is. Anyone who gave this product a negative review is obviously not using it correctly or doesn't like having clean strings/fretboard. Don't hesitate if you are on the fence about buying, this stuff works great and lasts a long time.

author: Igor Tikhonov
text: First of all i want to explain my goals in sound recordings. I‚Äôm a sound designer and field recordist in TV/Movies post-pro. So i need to have a pair of small microphones for stealth recording and for sound design works, where large mics are not acceptable. So the choice of DPA4060 was obvious - its an industry standard in terms of audio quality vs. size with incredible low end and fantastic space translation. So lets get started!1. Accessories. By default the grill, which installed on mics, is 3 dB soft boost from 8kHz to 20kHz (there is another type of grill - high boost: 10 dB at 12 kHz for chest mounting, but unfortunately it doesnt come with SMK4060 stereo kit, so you need to buy its separately). Two MicroDots to XLR connectors with belt clips (or two plastic rings, if you don‚Äôt need them). Also you have: boundary layer mounts - they are using for capturing sound from sound reflecting surfaces, such as tables, walls, floors and etc. Next you have microphone chest holders (btw, each capable of holding two mics at the same time), universal mounts with sticky plates for placing on any surface, two magnet mounts, for attaching to metal objects, for example drums, piano frames and etc.So you could see: this is a sound designer‚Äôs heaven - you can attache mics to virtually anything you could imagine2. Build qualityIts very robust. The cable is reinforced with kevlar. They don‚Äôt afraid of cold, heat or humidity. Period.3. ConnectionsThe mics are using MicroDot connectors, or you can use MicroDot-to-XLR adapters, which are included in the box. Note: if you are using XLRs - you must supply them with 48V phantom power.4. The most important - THE SOUNDThey are REALLY tiny mics! Its incredible how DPA could integrate such a big sound in a small capsule. The most amazing are the low end and space translation. I had several small lavaliere mics and none of them comes close. Sound locating is great, the frequency response is really flat. When i‚Äôm monitoring sound stage with a good pre-amp or recorder - sometimes i‚Äôm thinking that there is no headphones and i‚Äôm  just listening with my ears. Transients are also very good. There is not much of ¬´sound magnifier¬ª effect, like on cardioids, because its omnidirectional mics, but if you are recording ambiences - its great and exactly what you need. I also do much of stealth recording, when you are hiding mics under closes or in your bag and DPA4060s are great in such application, because they are small to hide and really crispy in the high end, so they will compensate all hi-freq lost because of hiding under closes.5. DownsidesThere is not much of it: first of all - the mics are a bit noisy (23dB of self noise) , so if you want to record really quiet and delicate sounds or ambiences - its pretty hard to do. Second: mics output is not really hot, so you need to crank up the preamps levels and if you have some cheap recorders with noisy preamps - it could be a problem with noise too.  And the price - yes, its pricy.6. ConclusionsThe best sounding micro-mics for sound design, instruments and ambience recording in this price range. Period.
topic: Best omnidirectional mics for sound design and ambience
